claim.claim-text:
1. A method for determining a position of a joint prosthesis using a computer assisted orthopedic surgery system in support of an arthroplasty surgery of a joint of a patient comprising the steps of:
attaching a first locatable element to a first bone on one side of the joint;
providing a sensor comprising a second locatable element;
moving the sensor in proximity of the joint;
locating a plurality of positions of the sensor relative to the first locatable element using a tracking device, the plurality of positions being patient specific data;
selecting a generic model of a joint that is not specific to the patient;
determining, with the use of a computer, the generic model in response to the plurality of positions located using the tracking device to generate a deformed model;
determining a position for a joint prosthesis on the deformed model; and
outputting on a display the determined position upon the deformed model, the display being connected to the computer.

3. The method of claim 2, further comprising the steps of:
determining a most distal point on the femur and a reference point on the tibia;
calculating a position of a distal section plane for the femur, wherein the position is a distance from the most distal point equal to a thickness of a distal condyle of the femoral component;
calculating a position of a tibial section plane for the tibia, wherein the position is a distance from the reference point equal to a thickness of a tibial plateau of the tibial component;
determining an angular variation between the distal section plane and the tibial section plane; and
displaying the angular variation on the display.

8. The method of claim 1, wherein the first bone is a femur and the method further comprises the steps of:
determining a most distal point on the femur and a most posterior point on the femur;
calculating a position of a distal section plane, wherein the position is a distance from the most distal point equal to a first predetermined position;
calculating a position of a posterior section plane, wherein the position is a distance from the most posterior point equal to a second predetermined position; and
calculating a size of a femoral component to be implanted such that a most proximal end of the femoral component is in alignment with an anterior surface of the deformed model.

11. The method of claim 1, wherein the joint is a knee joint having a femur as the first bone and a tibia as a second bone on an opposite side of the joint, wherein the joint prosthesis is a knee prosthesis model having a femoral component model and a tibial component model, and further comprising the steps of:
positioning the knee joint in varus or valgus;
determining a most distal position of a medial condyle and a most distal position of a lateral condyle of the femoral component model positioned at the determined position for the femoral component model;
determining a first proximal position of the tibial component model corresponding to the medial condyle and a second proximal position of the tibial component model corresponding to the lateral condyle;
determining a first distance between the most distal position of the medial condyle and the first proximal position of the tibial component model and a second distance between the most distal position of the lateral condyle and the second proximal position of the tibial component model when the knee joint is in either varus or valgus; and
displaying the first and second distances on the display.

14. The method of claim 1, wherein the joint is a knee joint having a femur as the first bone and a tibia as a second bone on an opposite side of the joint, wherein the joint prosthesis is a knee prosthesis having a femoral component and a tibial component, and the method further comprises the steps of:
attaching the femoral component to the femur;
attaching the tibial component to the tibia;
determining a most distal position of a medial condyle and a most distal position of a lateral condyle of the femoral component positioned at the determined position for the femoral component;
determining a first proximal position of the tibial component corresponding to the medial condyle and a second proximal position of the tibial component corresponding to the lateral condyle;
determining a first distance between the most distal position of the medial condyle and the first proximal position of the tibial component and a second distance between the most distal position of the lateral condyle and the second proximal position of the tibial component when the knee joint is in either varus or valgus; and
displaying the first and second distances on the display.
